  <text>
    <body>
      <head xml:id="MurdoMacLeod_GlasgowMMacLeodloose-d0e29">“Argyll’s Highlands or MacCailein Mor and the Lords of Lorne” by Cuthbert Bede (Rev. Edward Bradley of Grantham).</head>
      <entry xml:id="MurdoMacLeod_GlasgowMMacLeodloose-d0e34">
        <form>
          <orth>leurach</orth>
        </form>
        <def>“The marriage customs were these: When a young pair had got through the leurach, or contract, and had agreed to get married with the consent of their relatives, a night was appointed for
          the reite, when the friends met and a feast was prepared, of which all were hearty partakers.” (page 199)</def>
      </entry>
      <entry xml:id="MurdoMacLeod_GlasgowMMacLeodloose-d0e43">
        <form>
          <orth>sgreachan réilig</orth>
        </form>
        <def>“a shrieker of a burying place.” (page 204)</def>
      </entry>
      <entry xml:id="MurdoMacLeod_GlasgowMMacLeodloose-d0e52">
        <form>
          <orth>crann tràigh</orth>
        </form>
        <def>“… that the fairy cross was also called crann tràigh.” (page 220)</def>
      </entry>
      <entry xml:id="MurdoMacLeod_GlasgowMMacLeodloose-d0e61">
        <form>
          <orth>stike raide</orth>
        </form>
        <def>“it was customary to assign him a certain share of the spoil, which was called a stike raide or stike creich – ‘road collop’.” (page 252)</def>
      </entry>
      <entry xml:id="MurdoMacLeod_GlasgowMMacLeodloose-d0e70">
        <form>
          <orth>stike creich</orth>
          <pron>[See stike raide]</pron>
        </form>
        <def>[See stike raide]</def>
      </entry>
      <entry xml:id="MurdoMacLeod_GlasgowMMacLeodloose-d0e79" type="person">
        <form>
          <orth>Siol-Ghall</orth>
          <pron>[sic]</pron>
        </form>
        <def>[sic] “ – he whose parents were Highland on the one side and Lowland on the other – was called Sìol Ghall.” (page 271)</def>
      </entry>
      <entry xml:id="MurdoMacLeod_GlasgowMMacLeodloose-d0e88">
        <form>
          <orth>sìol-dubh</orth>
        </form>
        <def>plancton.</def>
      </entry>
